708332f-a.text:
First Presbyterian Church, founded in 1716, Fifth Avenue, West side, from 11th to 12th Streets.

December 28, 1927

F. L. Sperr, Photographer.

711085f-a.text:
11th Street, west from Fifth Avenue, showing the 40 Fifth Avenue apartment house (erected 1928) on the S.W. corner and part of The First Presbyterian Church (erected 1845) on the N.W. corner.  In the background may be seen the Sixth Avenue Elevated, then St. Vincent's Hospital on the N.E. corner of 11th Street and Seventh Avenue, and the building on the N.W. corner of Greenwich Avenue and 11th Street.

In the right foreground, on the N.E. corner, may be seen one of those bronze traffic signals which were installed on Fifth Avenue during the Mayer James. J. Walker's administration.

June 11, 1933

F.L. Sparr

11 East 11th Street, adjoining N.E. corner of Fifth Avenue. The gateway with the lamp is not part of 11 East 11th Street; it is the service entrance to 43 Fifth Lvenue, the corner building. This little house, set back fom the street, is an old stable, remodelled shortly after 1910 as a garage, and again remodelled
for a dwelling around 1920 or a little earlier.
March 21, 1931.
P. L. Sperr.
